                        Magazine article
                    
The CPA Journal

The Effects of Regulatory Overload 
By Radin, Arthur J.

Read preview








                            Magazine article
                        
The CPA Journal

The Effects of Regulatory Overload 
By Radin, Arthur J.

Read preview




Article excerpt

High Costs and Few BenefitsDuring the past decade, many accounting and reporting rules and restrictions have been enacted specifically for businesses and also for the accounting profession as a whole. These rules and restrictions come from many sources, including Congress, the SEC, the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA), and state governments.Such new rules and regulations are invariably referred to as "reforms." Although some might be quite effective in this respect, the usefulness of many such reforms is dubious - and they all cost money to implement. At their worst, they can be useless, expensive, and possibly even damaging. Unfortunately, the costs to implement such reforms are very difficult to determine, and any benefits are impossible to quantify. Some reforms - but certainly not all - are shown in the Exhibit.The Cost of ReformSo why should the accounting profession care? Society is being burdened with massive costs that do not translate into useful products or services. From a global perspective, the issue is whether these rules and regulations are stifling the U.S. economy. The answer is impossible to determine because the actual costs of these reforms are too diverse and impractical to quantify. The costs include the direct expenditures relating to compliance, as well as largely ignored hidden costs, such as -* additional employee compensation while people learn the rules,* development and enactment of procedures to comply with the rules,* related restrictions on economic activities, and* resolution of noncompliance issues.The government has always paid Up service to eliminating inefficiencies and minimizing red tape. For example, section 3(f) of the Securities Exchange Act of 1933 requires that the SEC evaluate the effect of rulemaking as follows:Consideration of promotion of efficiency, competition, and capital formation. - Whenever pursuant to this title the Commission is engaged in rulemaking, or in the review of a rule of a self-regulatory organization, and is required to consider or determine whether an action is necessary or appropriate in the public interest, the Commission shall also consider, in addition to the protection of investors, whether the action will promote efficiency, competition, and capital formation. (http://www.sec.gov/about/laws/sa33.pdf)Nevertheless, this section of the law appears to the author to be routinely ignored (other than as indicated below).The list in the Exhibit highlights just how impossible it is to even try to quantify the costs of these measures. For example, the Sarbanes-Oxley Act of 2002 (SOX) outlawed loans to certain officers. Although this item appears to be minor, there are real costs, such as the following:* Every lawyer and accountant practicing before the SEC must become familiar with the rule.* Company management and directors must become familiar with the rule.* Accounting firms handling public companies must add to their checklists a line item referring to loans to senior officers.* Corporate management must now find a new solution in situations where a loan to an officer might once have been the best economic solution for both the individual and the company.This is a perfect example of regulatory overload. To address the rare questionable transaction, Congress has made a routine transaction criminal. Is this "sledgehammer approach" appropriate? It has been often taken with respect to unusual, inappropriate transactions throughout various regulatory regimes, and I do not believe that it is possible to evaluate any of the costs or benefits of these new laws.SOX Section 404Much effort has been expended to determine the costs and potential benefits of the recent rule involving SOX section 404, which requires auditors to evaluate a company's internal controls over financial reporting. In September 2009, the SEC published the results of its study - required by SOX - of the costs and benefits of section 404. … 






